  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining Profile Fields**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the profile fields, realizing they\'re meant to be the core editable details. This includes the athlete\'s name, their diet or weight progress, and any other similar progress indicators. I\'m aiming to define these elements precisely for future customization.\n\n\n**Refining Editability Implementation**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the implementation of inline editing within `ProfileView.tsx`. My idea is to make the profile section editable and personalizable by either inline edit forms or an edit state triggered by click events. The goal is elegant and beautiful text input experiences. I\'m focusing on the intended CSS selector and how it interacts with the current implementation. The user\'s goal is to make this section editable and personalizable!\n\n\n**Designing Edit Functionality**\n\nI\'m now implementing inline editing within the profile view. Specifically, I\'m integrating editable fields for username, current and target weights, streak days, workouts completed, and more. I envision a highly visual and functional editing interface. I plan on including an edit mode button, and transforming the display to input fields with high-tech styling upon clicking. I also plan to make the avatar dynamically update based on the username.\n\n\n**Implementing Edit Controls**\n\nI\'m now integrating an \"Edit Mode\" toggle with `isEditing` state. When activated, custom inputs will display for name, weight, workouts, streak, level, and XP. This matches the \"editable and personalizable\" requirement. This is the next stage in development. I\'m focusing on making the edit toggle functional.\n\n\n**Integrating Edit and Save**\n\nI\'m now ensuring all user inputs in the editing interface update the profile using `setProfile`, which persists data through local storage in `App.tsx`. I\'ve checked available icons in `lucide-react`, and made sure to have the necessary ones like `Edit3` and `Save` included. I\'m focusing on crafting a seamless switch between view and inline edit modes.\n\n\n**Adding Edit Toggle**\n\nI\'m now thinking about how to integrate an edit toggle into the profile section header. I\'m imagining a \"Personalize Profile\" button that transforms into \"Save Bio\" when clicked. I\'m focusing on lines 39-44 of the component to implement an elegant button, and it must look like a tech-accent badge. I\'ll focus on styling for the inline edit text fields to display, using `lucide-react` icons. I also want to match the \"editable and personalizable\" requirement.\n\n\n**Refining UI Interactivity**\n\nI\'m now implementing the dynamic \"Edit Profile\" toggle, and designing the corresponding inline controls. I\'m focusing on lines 39-44 of the component to implement an elegant button that\'s also tech-accented. It\'s designed to switch to \"Save Profile\" and back, matching the `isEditing` state. The UI has a great look!\n\n\n**Visualizing the Avatar**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on dynamically generating the avatar within the profile header based on the user\'s name. I want it to be a visually distinct element that updates in sync with any name changes. I\'m focusing on the component section from lines 45-84.\n\n\n**Implementing XP Visualization**\n\nI\'m now integrating the XP tracking bar. My goal is to make a visual element with dynamic content based on the current user\'s profile information. I\'m focusing on the component section and the existing code to see how it looks and fits in. It\'ll be a high-contrast elegant interface. I plan on including an update to the avatar dynamically when the profile name is changed.\n\n\n**Styling Inputs Elegantly**\n\nI\'m now implementing the input fields for profile name and level during edit mode. I\'m focusing on styling these inputs for an elegant look! I\'m adding `input` fields for the profile name, with a character limit, and a number field for level, maintaining a clean and fully personalizable design for editing.\n\n\n**Refining Stats Customization**\n\nI\'m now implementing the ability to customize XP and XPNext values, and I\'m designing the display of all stats cleanly! I\'m planning to make them editable number/text inputs within the cards, for a fully personalizable look and feel! I\'m integrating this with the existing statistics highlights implementation!\n\n\n**Implementing Workout Updates**\n\nI\'m now integrating the inline edit functionality for \"Workouts Completed.\" I\'ve added a number input field within the existing implementation. It accurately reflects and updates the profile\'s `workoutsCompleted` value when in edit mode. I\'m ensuring the input field uses the minimum allowed value. I\'ve focused on styling and data binding with the existing input fields.\n\n\n**Adding Weight Editing**\n\nI\'m now integrating the inline edit functionality for \"Weight Progress\". I\'ve added a text input field within the existing implementation, styled and bound to the profile\'s `weightProgress` value. I\'m ensuring the input field has a character limit and placeholder text. I\'ve focused on styling and data binding with the existing input fields.\n\n\n**Integrating Streak Input**\n\nI\'m now integrating the inline edit functionality for \"Streak Days.\" I\'ve added a number input field within the implementation, accurately updating the profile\'s `streak` value when in edit mode. I\'m ensuring the input field has a minimum value of 0. I\'m focused on styling and data binding with the existing implementation.\n\n\n**Refining XP Input**\n\nI\'m now implementing inline editing for both the current XP and the target XPNext values, integrating number input fields for each and setting minimum values. I\'m focusing on the component\'s state to ensure accurate updates and validation, and I plan to style the component to match the elegant design.\n\n\n**Adding Save Notifications**\n\nI\'m now integrating a save notification system for edits. I plan to provide brief feedback when `isEditing` is saved, even though data auto-saves. This adds a nice touch, showing that edits are live. I\'m reviewing imports to ensure the necessary components are available, and plan to implement the notification system immediately!\n\n\n**Reviewing Imports and Content**\n\nI\'m now meticulously reviewing all imports and content within `ProfileView.tsx`. My goal is to determine if all necessary components are available and used. I\'m focusing on lines 1 to 90 to ensure a complete and pristine replacement. I want to guarantee our target matches are exact, as I prepare to replace specific blocks of code.\n\n\n**Integrating Avatar Logic**\n\nI\'m now integrating logic to dynamically generate and display the avatar initials based on the profile name\'s first two letters, replacing the placeholder \"FW\". I\'m focusing on the component section and the existing code to ensure this updates dynamically. I will ensure a consistent visual experience when updating the user\'s name.\n\n\n\n**Visualizing XP Progress**\n\nI\'m now focusing on integrating the XP tracking bar. I\'m aiming for a high-contrast and elegant interface that dynamically reflects the user\'s progress. I\'m focusing on lines 66-77 to make this visualization a reality!\n\n\n**Refining Visual Integration**\n\nI\'m now integrating the dynamic avatar initials and XP visualization within the existing layout. My focus is on achieving a smooth and visually appealing user experience. I\'m focusing on the component section and the existing code to ensure this updates dynamically. I\'m focusing on lines 66-84 to make this visualization a reality!\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will modify `/src/components/ProfileView.tsx` to add full editability to all profile metrics (Name, Level, XP, Workouts Completed, Weight Progress/Diet, and Streak Days) rendering inline interactive controls with auto-updating initials in the dynamic avatar. I will also style this elegantly using high-contrast slate-gradient colors and premium glass-input controls."
